ror-handling test worth flagging as a real gap, not just a skeleton:** `cmd_pdf_render` calls `subprocess.run(..., timeout=120)` (agent.py:222-226) with no `except subprocess.TimeoutExpired` — a hang currently crashes the command with an unhandled traceback instead of the clean `return 1` path used for other render failures. Worth a test that asserts the *desired* behavior once decided:\n```python\ndef test_pdf_render_handles_subprocess_timeout_gracefully(tmp_path, monkeypatch):\n    import subprocess\n    src = tmp_path / \"in.html\"; src.write_text(\"<html></html>\")\n    monkeypatch.setattr(\"agent._chrome_bin\", lambda: \"/bin/true\")\n    def raise_timeout(*a, **k): raise subprocess.TimeoutExpired(cmd=\"chrome\", timeout=120)\n    monkeypatch.setattr(\"subprocess.run\", raise_timeout)\n    rc = cmd_pdf_render([str(src)])\n    assert rc == 1  # currently this raises instead of returning cleanly\n```\n\n---\n\n",
